\subsection{Correlation sensitivity (bootstrap diagnostic)}
\label{sec:correlation-sensitivity}

The baseline bootstrap treats FLAG/PDG mass uncertainties as uncorrelated Gaussians; several quark mass determinations share lattice systematics. We test a common-correlation covariance with $\rho \in \{0, 0.25, 0.50, 0.75\}$ plus a structured covariance (within-sector $\rho = 0.5$ for $\{u,d,s\}$ and $\rho = 0.1$ for $\{c,b,t\}$, cross-sector $\rho = 0.05$). Across all variants, the hit count of trials with $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q$ remains between 7 and 9; the parametric-bootstrap expectation used in Section~\ref{sec:results} is stable. Because Model~B claim-level tail fractions are approximately $|r|/\sigma_Q$ in disguise (Section~\ref{sec:model-b}), we do not tabulate them by claim; the relevant quantity for the sensitivity check is the hit count, which is stable.

\subsection{Rejection sampling and the conditional prior}
\label{sec:loss-bias}

The Model~A prior is conditional on perturbative validity. Approximately $33\%$ of unconditioned log-uniform draws produce mass spectra outside the perturbative QCD regime---charm-bottom thresholds too close for valid threshold matching, $\alpha_s$ blow-up at low scales, or configurations where the perturbative running prescription is ill-posed. Real quarks occupy the perturbative regime, so the rejection restricts the reference class to spectra for which the Koide combination is computable in the same scheme used for the observed quarks.

\paragraph{Rejection-sampling reframe consistency check.} We re-implemented Model~A as explicit rejection sampling: continue drawing from the unconditioned log-uniform prior until $N = 10{,}000$ retained valid spectra are obtained (acceptance rate $67.6\%$). The resulting tail fractions agree with the conditional-prior implementation within MC noise: the maximum absolute difference across surveyed claims is $0.020$, with the full-search tail fraction agreeing to within $0.002$. The two implementations are mathematically equivalent.

\paragraph{Engine-switching crosscheck.} Re-running Model~A using 2-loop CRunDec on paired draws ($N = 10{,}000$) produces an identical rejected set: the same $3{,}269$ draws are rejected at both loop orders. Within CRunDec the perturbative-validity boundary is loop-order-independent. An analytic 1-loop scheme (closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching) has a lower rejection rate ($13.4\%$) because its simpler threshold matching tolerates configurations that full CRunDec identifies as perturbatively problematic; the analytic scheme is therefore strictly more permissive. The full-search tail fraction under analytic 1-loop is $\approx 0.37$ versus $\approx 0.50$ under 4-loop CRunDec. The qualitative result (full-search closure not extreme within the audited reference class) holds under both engines; 4-loop CRunDec is used throughout as the conventional standard for $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running.

\subsection{Loop-order convergence}
\label{sec:loop-order}

For \emph{self-scale} claims (Cao, Rivero, chain-no-run, 20-triple self), tail fractions are stable to four decimal places across 1-, 2-, 3-, 4-, and 5-loop CRunDec on identical paired draws ($N = 10{,}000$); these claims do not invoke running across flavor thresholds and the loop-order choice does not change their numerical evaluation.

For \emph{running} claims, the comparison across loop orders is not apples-to-apples, because the observed Koide combination itself is evaluated at a different numerical value at each loop order. At 2-loop, the observed combination has not perturbatively converged: $m_c(m_\tau) = 1.159$~GeV with $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-4}$ at 2-loop versus $m_c(m_\tau) = 1.143$~GeV with $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ at 4-loop---an order-of-magnitude difference. The 2-loop Model~A panel and the 4-loop Model~A panel answer different numerical questions about different observed values; their tail fractions should not be directly compared.

Among the four orders at which the observed Koide combination has converged ($\{1, 3, 4, 5\}$), the full-search tail fraction spread is $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$, with 4-loop and 5-loop closest to each other. The 2-loop value ($T = 0.04$) reflects the unconverged observed value and is reported but not incorporated into the headline numbers. All Model~A values reported in the main text and Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} use 4-loop CRunDec.

The headline result---that the full-search closure is at the median of the reference class---survives every loop order at which the observed Koide combination has converged. The loop-order spread contributes to the absolute-value uncertainty on running-claim tail fractions and is the largest characterized systematic on the Model~A numbers.


\section{Claim-level ranking}
\label{sec:isolation}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrcc}
\toprule
