\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m_i)/(\sum \sqrt{m_i})^2 = 2/3$ holds for the charged lepton pole masses to $6 \times 10^{-6}$. Extensions to the quark sector introduce degrees of freedom absent from the lepton relation---choice of triple, sign assignment for square roots, evaluation scale---without systematic accounting of how each choice inflates the false-positive rate. This note reports such an accounting for quark-only Koide-type claims.

Our main finding is independent of any Monte Carlo. Across consecutive FLAG/PDG releases from 2013 to 2024, the lepton Koide residual has tracked decreasing $\sigma_Q$ downward while the propagated uncertainty has shrunk; the Rivero $(s, c, b)$ signed-self residual ($\sim 8 \times 10^{-3}$) and the Cao $(c, b, t)$ self-scale residual ($\sim 4 \times 10^{-3}$) have not moved outside narrow bands across the same decade, even as $\sigma_Q$ has decreased by roughly a factor of three. On current FLAG~2024 values both quark-side residuals sit at $9$--$14\sigma_Q$ and are non-convergent; the lepton residual sits at $\sim 1\sigma_Q$ and has converged at each release. This observation requires no reference-class choice.

A complementary Monte Carlo audit over $\binom{6}{3} = 20$ quark triples, four sign assignments, and an audited discrete list of evaluation scales (12{,}960 trials) places the observed best residual at the median of a log-uniform random-spectrum reference distribution (empirical tail fraction $T \approx 0.50$ at $N = 100{,}000$ retained draws, binomial SE $\approx 0.002$; 4-loop CRunDec running). Literature-fixed single-triple claims rank higher within the same reference class: Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale at $T \approx 0.007$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self at $T \approx 0.03$. These rankings are conditional on the chosen reference class (log-uniform spectra conditional on perturbative validity) and on a loop-order-dependent quantity we characterize; they are within-audit rank statements, not calibrated significance levels. Assumption-light restatement: only $8$ of $12{,}960$ trials produce $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q$, consistent with the $\approx 7$ expected from parametric-bootstrap perturbations of the observed masses.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Koide~\citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} observed that the charged lepton pole masses satisfy
\begin{equation}
Q(e, \mu, \tau) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
to a residual of $6 \times 10^{-6}$. Extensions of this relation to the quark sector include Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} for $(s, c, b)$ with signed $\sqrt{m_s}$; Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011} surveying multiple triples; and Cao~\citep{Cao2012} for $(c, b, t)$ at self-scales.

Each such extension introduces one or more degrees of freedom relative to the original formula: which triple, which sign pattern for the square roots, which evaluation scale for each mass. The question this note addresses is the standard look-elsewhere question~\citep{GrossVitells2010}: \emph{given the degrees of freedom employed, how often would random or perturbed inputs produce a comparably tight closure?}

The note has two complementary components. The first (Section~\ref{sec:temporal}) is an assumption-light temporal analysis: does $|Q - 2/3|$ converge toward zero as measurement precision improves over FLAG/PDG releases? This requires no reference-class choice and constitutes the strongest discriminator available on current data. The second (Sections~\ref{sec:space}--\ref{sec:discussion}) is a Monte Carlo audit over a specific enumerated search space under a specific random-spectrum reference class. The Monte Carlo tail fractions apply only within that audited search space and reference class.

\paragraph{Terminology and notation.} We report empirical tail fractions of observed residuals against null distributions specified in Section~\ref{sec:mc}, denoted $T$ rather than $p$ to emphasize that they are descriptive rank quantiles within a chosen reference class rather than calibrated frequentist tail probabilities. The symbol $p$ is reserved for genuine frequentist $p$-values and for the standard binomial-SE formula $\sqrt{T(1-T)/N}$ applied to $T$ as a sample fraction. We do not use significance thresholds for inferential decisions, only as conventional ordering cuts in tables.


\section{Temporal trajectory: the assumption-light test}
\label{sec:temporal}

A relation that is exact in nature should produce a residual that shrinks as the propagated $\sigma_Q$ shrinks with successive measurement improvements. A relation that is a coincidence at a particular epoch's central values should produce a residual that remains pinned at its accidental value while $\sigma_Q$ decreases past it. This test depends on no analyst choice about reference class, prior, or running scheme; it requires only the published FLAG/PDG central values and uncertainties at each epoch.

The original lepton Koide relation is the textbook success. When Koide proposed $Q = 2/3$ in 1981--1983, the world-average $m_\tau$ was $1784.2 \pm 3.2$~MeV while the value required by the formula given $m_e$ and $m_\mu$ was $1776.97$~MeV. BES measurements published in 1992 and 1996 converged to $1776.96 \pm 0.31$~MeV (a $\approx 0.03\sigma$ confirmation of the prediction), and subsequent refinements have remained within $\sim 1\sigma$ (PDG~2024: $1776.86 \pm 0.12$~MeV). The residual $|Q - 2/3|$ has tracked the shrinking uncertainty downward across four decades.

The Rivero $(s, c, b)$ and Cao $(c, b, t)$ quark-side claims do not show this pattern. Table~\ref{tab:temporal-summary} reports $|Q - 2/3|$ for each claim at FLAG 2013, 2016, 2019, 2021, and 2024, along with the propagated $\sigma_Q$ at each epoch. Across the decade, the quark-side residuals have remained in narrow bands---the Rivero residual between $7.5$ and $8.2 \times 10^{-3}$, the Cao residual between $3.5$ and $4.7 \times 10^{-3}$---while the propagated $\sigma_Q$ has decreased by roughly a factor of three to its present value of $\sim 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$. On current values, the Rivero residual is $14\sigma_Q$ from zero and the Cao residual is $9\sigma_Q$; both ratios have grown, not shrunk, as measurement precision improved.

