\section{Reference models}
\label{sec:mc}

We use two reference models: a random-spectrum null (Model~A) and a parametric-bootstrap diagnostic (Model~B). Model~A is the inferential component; Model~B is a local-stability diagnostic and is explicitly \emph{not} a second inferential test.

\subsection{Model A: random-spectrum reference null}
\label{sec:model-a}

Six masses are drawn log-uniformly from $[2\;\text{MeV},\; 170\;\text{GeV}]$, sorted, and assigned to quark slots, with the spectrum conditioned on perturbative validity: the running prescription must produce finite, convergent values for all six masses across the audited evaluation scales. Conditioning is implemented by rejection sampling; the acceptance rate is $\approx 67\%$. Full four-loop CRunDec running is performed on every retained draw, with thresholds computed from the random masses themselves rather than from the SM values. The main run uses $N = 100{,}000$ retained pseudo-experiments (binomial SE $\approx 0.002$ at $T = 0.5$); an earlier $N = 10{,}000$ run agrees within $1$--$2$ binomial SE.

\paragraph{Question this model answers.} ``Given the audited search space, is the observed best residual unusual relative to residuals produced by spectra drawn from the specified reference class?''

\paragraph{Explicit scope limits.} The reference class is log-uniform spectra over the SM-spanning mass range, conditional on perturbative validity under 4-loop CRunDec. This is one specific class of analyst convenience; it is not derived from a physical principle. Alternative reference classes---spectra drawn from Yukawa-hierarchy distributions, spectra constrained by grand-unified relations, spectra derived from landscape phenomenology---would constitute different audits with different reference classes and would in general yield different absolute tail fractions. We do not undertake those audits here, and Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity} reports sensitivity only within the log-uniform family and two hierarchy-preserving variants, not across genuinely different reference classes. Model~A tail fractions are within-reference-class rank statements, not calibrated significance levels.

An initial implementation used a surrogate running scheme for speed; the surrogate did not reproduce full-CRunDec results at the per-draw level when checked (Section~\ref{sec:surrogate-validation}), and all numbers reported in this paper use the full-CRunDec rebuild.

\subsection{Model B: parametric-bootstrap local-stability diagnostic}
\label{sec:model-b}

Each quark mass is perturbed within its FLAG/PDG uncertainty (Gaussian, $1\sigma$, treated as uncorrelated in the baseline); $\alpha_s$ is perturbed within its uncertainty. Full four-loop CRunDec running is performed on every draw ($N_B = 2{,}000$ pseudo-experiments). The bootstrap perturbations are applied uniformly to all claims, including self-scale-only claims.

\paragraph{Formal definition.} For a claim with observed Koide combination $Q_{\text{obs}}$, let $r_{\text{obs}} = Q_{\text{obs}} - 2/3$. For each bootstrap draw $b$, perturbed masses are run to the audited scales and a perturbed $Q_b$ is computed with $r_b = Q_b - 2/3$. The Model~B tail fraction is
\begin{equation}
T_B = \frac{1}{N_B} \sum_{b=1}^{N_B} \mathbf{1}\left[ |r_b| \le |r_{\text{obs}}| \right].
\label{eq:tb-def}
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Status as a diagnostic.} $T_B$ is approximately a monotone function of $|r_{\text{obs}}|/\sigma_Q$: for $|r| \gg \sigma_Q$ the bootstrap draws concentrate around $r_{\text{obs}}$ and $T_B \to 0.5$; for $|r| \ll \sigma_Q$ the bootstrap draws straddle zero and $T_B$ is small. $T_B$ therefore restates the $|r|/\sigma_Q$ ratio in tail-fraction form and does not constitute independent inferential content beyond that ratio. We report $T_B$ only for the correlation-sensitivity check (Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}); all claim-level rankings in this paper use $|r|/\sigma_Q$ directly, not $T_B$. This represents a change from an earlier draft in which Model~B appeared in the main ranking table.

\paragraph{Parametric-bootstrap hit expectation.} The hit count of 8 trials with $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q$ discussed in Section~\ref{sec:results} is compared to the expected count under the Model~B bootstrap: applying the perturbations to all 12{,}960 trials and counting the fraction that land within their own $\sigma_Q$ gives $\approx 7$ expected sub-$\sigma_Q$ hits. This is a use of Model~B for which the $|r|/\sigma_Q$ reduction is not a substitute, and it is the one inferential role Model~B retains.


\section{Interpretation}
\label{sec:interpretation}

\paragraph{Three distinct inferential targets.}
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Is the full search unusual?} ``Across the audited 12{,}960 configurations, is the observed best closure unusual under the random-spectrum reference?'' Answered by Model~A applied to the full search; result is $T \approx 0.50$.
\item \textbf{Is a particular literature-fixed claim unusual within the audit?} ``Is the residual of a single triple/sign/scale configuration proposed in prior work unusual within the same reference class?'' Answered by Model~A applied per-claim; results in Table~\ref{tab:pvalues}.
\item \textbf{Is a particular configuration locally consistent with measurement noise?} ``How small is the observed residual relative to the propagated mass-measurement uncertainty?'' Answered by $|r|/\sigma_Q$ directly.
\end{enumerate}
These are different questions answered by different statistics. The Model~A full-search answer (target~1) does not depend on prior literature; per-claim answers (target~2) are conditional on which claims one singles out; the $|r|/\sigma_Q$ answers (target~3) are descriptive measurement-precision statements. We report all three and do not combine them into a single composite ranking.

\paragraph{Scope of the multiplicity correction.} The correction implemented by Model~A bounds multiplicity within the audited search space and reference class. It does \emph{not} bound the broader hypothesis-generation degrees of freedom---four decades of Koide literature, the choice of Koide-style algebraic targets, iterative researcher-driven scale selection. No look-elsewhere correction in any field bounds all unenumerable researcher choices; standard practice is that post-hoc multiplicity corrections bound the explicit search and the broader question is deferred to forward-looking tests on independent data~\citep{CousinsLectures}. The temporal-trajectory analysis of Section~\ref{sec:temporal} is the relevant forward-looking test; per-claim Model~A tail fractions should be read as within-audit rank statements only.

\paragraph{What Model~A cannot do.} Model~A cannot in principle settle whether a Koide quark relation reflects structure in nature, because the SM Yukawa couplings are not drawn from any distribution. What Model~A \emph{can} do is constrain how much look-elsewhere freedom the published literature has been exploiting: if even a generous search over combinatorial triples, signs, and audited scales produces a best residual at the median of a random-spectrum reference, then the corresponding multiplicity burden has not been absorbed in published claims. That is the intended scope of the test.


\section{Sensitivity tests}
\label{sec:robustness}

Each test below probes an assumption already embedded in Model~A or the trial enumeration. None broadens the scope of the audit.

\subsection{Validation of surrogate running}
\label{sec:surrogate-validation}

An earlier implementation of Model~A used a surrogate running scheme, applying multiplicative ratios from the four-loop calculation but skipping the full CRunDec call per draw, for computational efficiency. To verify the surrogate, we recomputed a fixed-seed subsample of 500 Model~A pseudo-experiments using full four-loop CRunDec and compared per-draw best residuals across the $12{,}960$ trials. The surrogate failed validation: the median fractional discrepancy in the per-draw best residual was $92\%$; the same trial was identified as best under both methods in only $0.2\%$ of draws; tail-fraction confidence intervals at thresholds $\{10^{-3}, 10^{-4}, 10^{-5}\}$ did not overlap. The surrogate applied SM-derived multiplicative ratios to random spectra whose thresholds and flavor structure differ, and the approximation broke down per-draw. All numbers reported in this paper use full-CRunDec running.

\subsection{Prior sensitivity within the log-uniform family}
\label{sec:prior-sensitivity}

Within the log-uniform family, we test three endpoint and shape variations beyond the baseline: endpoints widened by $5\times$ to $[0.4\;\text{MeV},\; 850\;\text{GeV}]$; endpoints widened by $10\times$ to $[0.2\;\text{MeV},\; 1.7\;\text{TeV}]$; and a log-normal prior centred on the geometric mean of the SM quark masses with $\sigma_{\log} = 2.5$. Each variant contains the full SM quark mass range, so the observed Koide configurations can in principle be produced by random draws in each. We do not test narrowed endpoints below $m_t$, which would exclude the actual top mass from the reference class and would change which question the tail fraction answers.

