\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{Summary of findings}

Three observations.

First, the temporal-trajectory test (Section~\ref{sec:temporal}) distinguishes the lepton Koide relation from the Rivero and Cao quark-side claims independently of any Monte Carlo machinery. The lepton residual has tracked $\sigma_Q$ downward across four decades; the quark-side residuals have remained pinned at their $\sim 10^{-3}$ values while $\sigma_Q$ shrank by a factor of three. On current values, $|r|/\sigma_Q$ has grown for both quark-side claims as measurement precision has improved.

Second, the Monte Carlo audit reaches a compatible conclusion within its chosen reference class. At full search freedom over the audited 12{,}960 trials, the observed best closure reproduces the median random-spectrum residual ($T \approx 0.50$). The assumption-light restatement is that only $8$ of $12{,}960$ trials produce sub-$\sigma_Q$ residuals, consistent with the $\approx 7$ expected from parametric-bootstrap perturbations. The qualitative full-search conclusion is preserved across five prior variations within the log-uniform family, both hierarchy-preserving variants, the rejection-sampling reframe, and all converged loop orders.

Third, literature-fixed single-triple claims rank higher within the Model~A reference class: Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale at $T \approx 0.007$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self at $T \approx 0.03$. These are within-reference-class rankings, not calibrated significance levels, subject to the systematics in Sections~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}--\ref{sec:loop-order}. Neither claim has a small $|r|/\sigma_Q$ ratio: the Cao residual sits at $\approx 9\sigma_Q$ and the Rivero residual at $\approx 14\sigma_Q$ on current FLAG/PDG values. The Rivero claim crosses the $0.05$ ordering cut under Variant~A of the hierarchy-preserving prior ($T \approx 0.08$); the Cao claim remains below $0.02$ under all tested variants.

\subsection{Consistency across the two components}

The temporal and Monte Carlo components reach compatible conclusions but are not redundant. The temporal test shows that $|r|/\sigma_Q$ for the quark-side claims has grown, not shrunk, with measurement precision---a pattern incompatible with a relation exact in nature. The Monte Carlo test shows that the full search over the audited combinatorial space produces a best residual indistinguishable from the median of the reference class---a pattern consistent with the look-elsewhere burden of the enumeration being larger than the apparent closure. Each observation has an independent empirical content; each is subject to different assumptions; they are compatible in direction.

No LEE correction bounds all unenumerable researcher choices, and Model~A does not attempt to. What Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} rules out is not ``structure in nature'' but ``structure in nature detectable under the chosen reference class with the audited search space''; what Table~\ref{tab:temporal-summary} rules out is the specific pattern a physically exact relation would produce. Neither is a proof; together they are a stronger joint indictment than either alone.

\subsection{Limitations}

The enumerated search space is finite and discrete; three degrees of freedom (algebraic target, mass scheme, fermion content) are held fixed. Continuous scale scans would inflate the penalty without bound; the present audit is a lower-complexity benchmark. The Model~A reference class is log-uniform spectra conditional on perturbative validity under 4-loop CRunDec. This is one class of analyst convenience. Sensitivity within the log-uniform family is tested in Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity} and found stable; sensitivity to hierarchy structure is tested in Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null} and found stable for the full-search conclusion but partial for the Rivero claim. Sensitivity across genuinely different reference-class families is \emph{not} tested and is acknowledged as the largest uncharacterized component of the uncertainty hierarchy. The loop-order systematic on running-claim tail fractions is $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$; self-scale claim tail fractions are stable across loop orders. The parametric-bootstrap baseline treats FLAG/PDG uncertainties as uncorrelated Gaussians; the hit-count expectation used in Section~\ref{sec:results} is stable across the correlation choices tested (Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}).


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

Two pieces of evidence reach compatible conclusions from different assumption sets. The temporal-trajectory test---independent of every analyst choice in the Monte Carlo---shows that $|r|/\sigma_Q$ has grown for the Rivero and Cao claims over the 2013--2024 FLAG/PDG release series while shrinking for the lepton Koide relation over four decades. The Monte Carlo audit---conditional on the log-uniform random-spectrum reference class and 4-loop CRunDec---places the full-search best closure at the median of the reference null ($T \approx 0.50$), with literature-fixed single-triple claims at $T \approx 0.007$ (Cao) and $T \approx 0.03$ (Rivero). Neither quark-side claim has a small $|r|/\sigma_Q$ ratio on current values; both sit at $9$--$14\sigma_Q$.

The analysis, all code, all seeds, and the audited trial list are in the repository~\citep{RepoMC}.


\section*{Computational note}

All computations are reproducible from~\citep{RepoMC}. Search space: \texttt{search\_space.json} ($12{,}960$ trials, audited in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}). Running: four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec}, with thresholds computed from the input mass spectrum (SM values for Models~A and~B baseline; perturbed values for bootstrap variants; random values for random-spectrum draws). Inputs: FLAG~2024, PDG~2024.

Random-spectrum MC (Model~A): $100{,}000$ retained experiments in the main run, full CRunDec on every retained draw, rejection-sampling acceptance $\approx 67\%$, binomial SE $\approx 0.002$ at $T = 0.5$. Bootstrap MC (Model~B): $2{,}000$ experiments per correlation variant, full CRunDec on every draw, perturbations applied uniformly to all claims including self-scale-only claims. Surrogate validation: 500 paired draws comparing surrogate to full CRunDec (surrogate failed validation and is not used in final numbers). Hierarchy-preserving null: 10{,}000 experiments per variant. Prior sensitivity: 10{,}000 experiments per variant across the four configurations of Table~\ref{tab:priors}. Loop-order convergence: 10{,}000 paired draws at 1-, 2-, 3-, 4-, and 5-loop CRunDec; 2-loop value reported separately because the observed Koide combination has not perturbatively converged at 2-loop. Analytic 1-loop crosscheck: pure-Python closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching, 10{,}000 paired draws. Rejection-sampling reframe consistency check: explicit rejection sampling ($14{,}783$ unconditioned attempts for $10{,}000$ retained valid spectra); tail fractions agree with the original implementation within MC noise. All seeds documented in the repository.


