\subsection{Enumerated search space}
\label{sec:search-enum}

The audited search space consists of the complete combinatorial enumeration of 3-element subsets of the six quarks, $\binom{6}{3} = 20$ triples, paired with four sign assignments for the square roots (the two relative-sign-invariant equivalence classes of $\{+,+,+\}$, $\{+,+,-\}$, $\{+,-,+\}$, $\{-,+,+\}$; overall sign flips leave $Q$ invariant) and an audited discrete list of evaluation scales drawn from physically interpretable reference scales appearing in the literature: quark self-scales, SM particle masses within each quark's perturbative running window, and the canonical FLAG reference at $2$~GeV for light quarks that have no perturbative self-scale. The top quark is held at its self-scale throughout (an operational convention reflecting that $m_t$ enters the quoted FLAG/PDG value directly rather than via running). The complete scale list is archived as \texttt{search\_space.json}~\citep{RepoMC}; the full enumeration as \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}. The audited trial count is
\begin{equation}
20\;\text{triples} \times 4\;\text{signs} \times (\text{variable scales per triple}) = 12{,}960\;\text{trials.}
\end{equation}

We use the full combinatorial set of 20 triples rather than only the triples discussed in the prior literature (Rivero, Rodejohann-Zhang, Cao, and a handful of others, perhaps 5--8 triples depending on how one counts). The combinatorial enumeration is strictly larger than the literature set, so it is conservative with respect to triple-selection multiplicity: any LEE penalty we compute over 20 triples upper-bounds the penalty that would apply to the actual literature set. This framing resolves a tension in the underlying question---the search space is simultaneously ``the relations that have been proposed'' and ``a combinatorial benchmark''---in favor of the more conservative interpretation.

\subsection{What is and is not audited}

Three degrees of freedom are deliberately held fixed:
\begin{itemize}
\item the algebraic target ($Q = 2/3$);
\item the mass scheme ($\overline{\text{MS}}$ throughout);
\item the fermion content (no neutrinos, no boson masses admitted into triples).
\end{itemize}
Each is an extension to which the same methodology could be applied; none is attempted here. The scale set is finite and discrete. Enlarging the scale set to continuous or arbitrary choices would inflate the trial count without bound; the present discrete audit is therefore a lower-complexity benchmark, not an exhaustive accounting of all conceivable scale freedom.


\section{Observed results}
\label{sec:results}

We write $\sigma_Q$ for the propagated uncertainty on $Q$ from the FLAG/PDG mass uncertainties and $\alpha_s$; it is computed by Monte Carlo resampling (Section~\ref{sec:mc}, Model~B), treating the inputs as Gaussian and uncorrelated in the baseline with correlation sensitivity tested in Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}. Because $Q$ is a nonlinear function of six masses and its sensitivity to each input differs across triples, $\sigma_Q$ is triple-specific; the representative SM-central value $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ is the magnitude that appears in the hit-count threshold below.

Of the 12{,}960 trials, 8 produce $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q$, distributed across exactly three triples. The expected number of sub-$\sigma_Q$ hits under parametric-bootstrap perturbations of the observed masses (Section~\ref{sec:mc}, Model~B) is approximately~7. The observed count therefore does not exceed what measurement-noise perturbations around the observed spectrum already produce---a clean, assumption-light statement that the number of ``interesting'' closures across the audited search space is consistent with what measurement noise alone generates.

